Module 3: Linear Algebra Part-2¶

Matrices¶

"Matrices" (singular: matrix) refer to rectangular arrays of numbers, symbols, or expressions, arranged in rows and columns. They are a fundamental concept in linear algebra and have various applications in pure mathematics, physics, computer science, economics, and other fields.

For example, consider the matrix A:

$ A = \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \\ \end{bmatrix} $

This matrix has 2 rows and 2 columns, making it a 2x2 matrix. The entry in the first row and first column is (a), the entry in the first row and second column is (b), and so on.

Types of Matrices¶

There are several types of matrices, including:

  • Row matrix: Only one row.
  • Column matrix: Only one column.
  • Square matrix: Same number of rows and columns.
  • Diagonal matrix: All non-diagonal elements are zero.
  • Identity matrix: A square matrix where diagonal elements are 1 and non-diagonal elements are 0.
  • Zero matrix: All elements are zero.
  • Symmetric matrix: It remains unchanged upon taking its transpose.
  • Skew-symmetric matrix: Its negative is its transpose.
  • Orthogonal matrix: Its transpose is its inverse.

Matrix Operations¶

Several operations can be performed with matrices, including:

  • Addition: You can add two matrices of the same dimension by adding corresponding elements.
  • Scalar Multiplication: Multiply each element of the matrix by a scalar (a single number).
  • Matrix Multiplication: Multiplying two matrices involves taking the dot product of rows of the first matrix with columns of the second.
  • Transpose: Reflect the matrix over its main diagonal.
  • Determinant: A scalar value derived from a square matrix.
  • Inverse: If it exists, the inverse of a matrix is such that when it's multiplied with the original matrix, the result is the identity matrix.

Applications of Matrices¶

Matrices are used in various fields and applications, including:

  • Linear Transformations: Representing transformations in geometry.
  • Solving Systems of Linear Equations: Using techniques like Gauss-Jordan elimination or Cramer's rule.
  • Computer Graphics: For transformations like rotation, scaling, and translation.
  • Quantum Mechanics: Representing quantum states and operations.
  • Economics: Input-output analysis.
  • Data Analysis: In areas such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA).

Understanding the properties and operations of matrices is foundational in linear algebra, and linear algebra itself is crucial for many advanced topics in mathematics and its applications.

Types of Matrices¶

A lot of linear algebra is concerned with operations on vectors and matrices, and there are many different types of matrices. There are a few types of matrices that you may encounter again and again when getting started in linear algebra, particularity the parts of linear algebra relevant to machine learning.

Square Matrix¶

A square matrix is a matrix where the number of rows $(n)$ is equivalent to the number of columns $(m)$.

$n=m$

The size of the matrix is called the order, so an order 4 square matrix is 4 4.

Symmetric Matrix¶

A symmetric matrix is a type of square matrix where the top-right triangle is the same as the bottom-left triangle.

To be symmetric, the axis of symmetry is always the main diagonal of the matrix, from the top left to the bottom right.

A symmetric matrix is always square and equal to its own transpose. The transpose is an operation that flips the number of rows and columns. It is explained in more detail in the next lesson.

$M = M^T$

Triangular Matrix¶

A triangular matrix is a type of square matrix that has all values in the upper-right or lower-left of the matrix with the remaining elements filled with zero values. A triangular matrix with values only above the main diagonal is called an upper triangular matrix. Whereas, a triangular matrix with values only below the main diagonal is called a lower triangular matrix. Below is an example of a 3 3 upper triangular matrix.

$a = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\ 0 & 2 & 3\\ 0 & 0 & 3 \end{bmatrix}$

sns.heatmap(lower_triangular, annot=True, cmap='viridis', cbar=False, ax=ax[2], annot_kws={"size": 15})

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpretation¶

From the visualizations:

  • The first heatmap represents our original matrix.
  • The second heatmap represents the upper triangular matrix derived from the original matrix. Notice that all values below the main diagonal are zeros.
  • The third heatmap represents the lower triangular matrix derived from the original matrix. Notice that all values above the main diagonal are zeros.

Triangular matrices are significant in numerical linear algebra, especially in methods for solving linear systems of equations. Their structure ensures reduced computational complexity in certain algorithms.

Conclusion¶

Through this exercise, we've visualized and understood the concept of triangular matrices. Recognizing and working with triangular matrices can simplify many mathematical operations and are fundamental in various algorithms in linear algebra.

Diagonal Matrix¶

A diagonal matrix is one where values outside of the main diagonal have a zero value, where the main diagonal is taken from the top left of the matrix to the bottom right. A diagonal matrix is often denoted with the variable D and may be represented as a full matrix or as a vector of values on the main diagonal. Below is an example of a 3 3 square diagonal matrix.

$a = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0\\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}$

Identity Matrix¶

An identity matrix is a square matrix that does not change a vector when multiplied. The values of an identity matrix are known. All of the scalar values along the main diagonal (top-left to bottom-right) have the value one, while all other values are zero.

$a = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0\\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}$

Orthogonal Matrix¶

Two vectors are orthogonal when their dot product equals zero. The length of each vector is 1 then the vectors are called orthonormal because they are both orthogonal and normalized.

$v.w^t = 0$

Orthogonal matrices are significant in linear algebra and computer graphics because they represent transformations that preserve lengths and angles. This property is especially useful in rotations and reflections.

Matrix Operations¶

Matrix operations are used in the description of many machine learning algorithms. Some operations can be used directly to solve key equations, whereas others provide useful shorthand or foundation in the description and the use of more complex matrix operations.

Transpose¶

A defined matrix can be transposed, which creates a new matrix with the number of columns and rows flipped. This is denoted by the superscript $T$ next to the matrix $A^T$.

$C = A^T$

Exercise 7 Transposing a Matrix using Nested List Comprehension in Python¶

Problem Statement¶

You are a data scientist working on optimizing matrix operations. One of the tasks you've been given is to transpose a matrix without using any external libraries like NumPy. Your challenge is to use nested list comprehension to achieve this.

Objective: Generate a matrix and transpose it using nested list comprehension. Visualize the original and transposed matrices.

Step 1: Generating a Matrix¶

For this exercise, we'll create a 3x2 matrix using nested lists.

In [24]:
# Generating a 3x2 matrix using nested lists
matrix = [[1, 2],
          [3, 4],
          [5, 6]]

Step 2: Transposing the Matrix using Nested List Comprehension¶

The transpose of a matrix is obtained by flipping it over its main diagonal. We can achieve this using nested list comprehension.

In [25]:
# Transposing the matrix using nested list comprehension
transpose_matrix = [[row[i] for row in matrix] for i in range(len(matrix[0]))]

Step 3: Visualizing the Matrix and its Transpose¶

We'll use a simple method to print both matrices for visualization.

In [26]:
# Printing the original and transposed matrices
print("Original Matrix:")
for row in matrix:
    print(row)

print("\nTransposed Matrix:")
for row in transpose_matrix:
    print(row)

Original Matrix:
[1, 2]
[3, 4]
[5, 6]

Transposed Matrix:
[1, 3, 5]
[2, 4, 6]

Interpretation¶

From the printed matrices:

  • The first set of lists represents our original matrix.
  • The second set of lists represents the transpose of our original matrix. We can observe that the rows of the original matrix have become columns in the transpose matrix and vice versa.

Using nested list comprehension, we've efficiently transposed the matrix without the need for any external libraries. This method is particularly useful when working with pure Python without additional dependencies.

Conclusion¶

Through this exercise, we've generated a matrix and transposed it using nested list comprehension. We've visualized the original and transposed matrices and understood the significance of the transpose operation in transforming the rows and columns of a matrix.

Inverse¶

Matrix inversion is a process that finds another matrix that when multiplied with the matrix, results in an identity matrix. Given a matrix $A$, find matrix $B$, such that $AB = I^n$ or $BA = I^n$

$AB = BA = I^n$

Trace¶

A trace of a square matrix is the sum of the values on the main diagonal of the matrix (top-left to bottom-right).

The trace operator gives the sum of all of the diagonal entries of a matrix.

The operation of calculating a trace on a square matrix is described using the notation $tr(A)$ where A is the square matrix on which the operation is being performed.

The trace is calculated as the sum of the diagonal values; for example, in the case of a 3 3 matrix: $tr(A) = a_1,_1+a_2,_2+a_3,_3$

Determinant¶

The determinant of a square matrix is a scalar representation of the volume of the matrix.

It is denoted by the $det(A)$ notation or $|A|$, where A is the matrix on which we are calculating the determinant.

$det(A)$

Rank¶

The rank of a matrix is the estimate of the number of linearly independent rows or columns in a matrix. The rank of a matrix M is often denoted as the function $rank().$

Exercise 11 Understanding the Rank of a Matrix in Python¶

The rank of a matrix is defined as the maximum number of linearly independent column vectors (or row vectors) in the matrix. It provides insights into the matrix's properties and is used in various applications in linear algebra, such as determining the solvability of a system of linear equations.

Original Matrix:

Using numpy, we can easily compute the rank of our matrix.

Interpretation¶

The rank of a matrix gives us the number of linearly independent rows or columns in the matrix. For instance:

  • If the rank of a matrix is equal to the minimum of its number of rows and columns, then the matrix has full rank.
  • If the rank is less than the minimum of its number of rows and columns, then the matrix is rank deficient.

Visualization¶

Let's visualize the matrix using a heatmap to get a better understanding of its values.

plt.title("Matrix Heatmap")
plt.show()

Through this exercise, we've generated a matrix, computed its rank, and visualized the matrix using a heatmap. Understanding the rank of a matrix is essential in linear algebra, as it provides insights into the linear independence of the matrix's rows and columns.

Understanding Eigenvectors and Eigenvalues with Python¶

Eigenvalues : are scalars $(numbers)$ associated with a square matrix. Given a square matrix $A$, an eigenvalue $() $of $A$ is a scalar that satisfies the following equation:

$A * v = * v$

Where:

  1. $A$ is the square matrix under consideration.
  2. $v$ is a non-zero vector called the eigenvector associated with the eigenvalue $.$

Eigenvectors: Eigenvectors are non-zero vectors that correspond to eigenvalues. For each eigenvalue $()$ of a square matrix $A$, there exists an associated eigenvector $v$ such that when the matrix $A$ is multiplied by this eigenvector, the result is a scaled version of the eigenvector:

$A * v = * v$

Exercise 13 Compound Interest Comparison Using Matrix Operations¶

Problem Statement¶

Imagine you have two savings accounts. The first account offers an annual interest rate of 5%, while the second offers an annual interest rate of 3%. Both accounts compound interest annually.

Given an initial investment of $10,000 in each account, how will the accounts grow over a period of 10 years when represented as a matrix? Which account will yield a higher return after 10 years?

Objectives:¶

  • Represent the growth of both accounts over 10 years using matrices.
  • Calculate the amount in each account for each year over a 10-year period using matrix operations.
  • Visualize the growth of each account over time.
  • Determine which account yields a higher return after 10 years.

Step 1: Define the Interest Rates¶

We start by defining the interest rates for both accounts. The first account has an interest rate of 5% (r1 = 0.05), and the second account has an interest rate of 3% (r2 = 0.03).

In [43]:
# Define the interest rates
r1 = 0.05
r2 = 0.03

Step 2: Create the Growth Matrix¶

Next, we create a matrix to represent the growth of both accounts over 10 years. Each row of the matrix represents a year, and each column represents an account. The values in the matrix represent the growth factor for each year and account.

In [44]:
# Create the growth matrix
growth_matrix = np.array([[1 + r1, 1 + r2]])
for i in range(1, 10):
    growth_matrix = np.vstack([growth_matrix, [growth_matrix[i-1, 0]*(1+r1), growth_matrix[i-1, 1]*(1+r2)]])

Step 3: Calculate the Amounts¶

Using the growth matrix, we can calculate the amount in each account for each year. We start with an initial investment of $10,000 in each account and multiply it by the growth factor for each year to get the amount for that year.

In [45]:
initial_investment = np.array([[10000, 10000]])

# Calculate the amounts for both accounts over 10 years
amounts = initial_investment * growth_matrix

Step 4: Visualize the Growth¶

To better understand the growth of the investments, we can plot the amounts in both accounts over the 10-year period. This will allow us to visually compare the growth of the two accounts.

In [46]:
# Visualize the growth
plt.plot(amounts[:, 0], label="Account 1 (5% interest)")
plt.plot(amounts[:, 1], label="Account 2 (3% interest)")
plt.xlabel("Years")
plt.ylabel("Amount ($)")
plt.title("Growth of Investment Over 10 Years")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Interpretation¶

From the plot, we can observe that the account with a 5% interest rate grows faster than the account with a 3% interest rate. By the end of the 10th year, the difference in the amounts in the two accounts becomes quite significant. This demonstrates the power of compound interest and how a small difference in interest rates can lead to a substantial difference in returns over time.

This exercise demonstrates how matrix operations can be used to represent and calculate the growth of investments in multiple accounts over time. It provides a visual representation of the power of compound interest and the impact of different interest rates on the growth of an investment.

Matrix Decomposition¶

Many complex matrix operations cannot be solved efficiently or with stability using the limited precision of computers.

Matrix decompositions are methods that reduce a matrix into constituent parts that make it easier to calculate more complex matrix operations.

Matrix decomposition methods, also called matrix factorization methods,

LU Decomposition¶

The $LU$ decomposition is for square matrices and decomposes a matrix into L and U components.

$A = L.U$

Where $A$ is the square matrix that we wish to decompose, $L$ is the lower triangle matrix and $U$ is the upper triangle matrix.

The LU decomposition is found using an iterative numerical process and can fail for those matrices that cannot be decomposed or decomposed easily. A variation of this decomposition that is numerically more stable to solve in practice is called the LUP decomposition, or the LU decomposition with partial pivoting.

$A = L.U.P$

The $LU$ decomposition is calculated, then the original matrix is reconstructed from the components.

Exercise 14 LU Decomposition¶

Problem Statement¶

LU Decomposition, also known as LU factorization, refers to the factorization of a matrix into three matrices - a lower triangular matrix (L), an upper triangular matrix (U), and a permutation matrix (P). QR Decomposition¶

The QR decomposition is for $n m$ matrices (not limited to square matrices) and decomposes a matrix into Q and R components.

QR decomposition decomposes a given matrix A into the product of an orthogonal matrix (Q) and an upper triangular matrix (R), i.e., A = QR.

$A=Q.R$

Where $A$ is the matrix that we wish to decompose, $Q$ a matrix with the size $m m,$ and $R$ is an upper triangle matrix with the size $m n.$

Application of Matrix Decomposition¶

1. Solving Linear Systems:

Matrix decomposition methods, such as LU decomposition, are used to solve systems of linear equations efficiently. By decomposing the coefficient matrix, solving for the unknown variables becomes more manageable.

2. Principal Component Analysis (PCA):

PCA involves eigenvalue decomposition or singular value decomposition (SVD) to identify the principal components in high-dimensional data. It is a fundamental technique in dimensionality reduction and data visualization.

3. Matrix Approximations:

Matrix factorization techniques like SVD, QR decomposition, and NMF are used to approximate large matrices, reducing their dimensionality while preserving essential information. These approximations are used in various data analysis tasks.**

Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)¶

The Singular-Value Decomposition, or SVD for short, is a matrix decomposition method for reducing a matrix to its constituent parts in order to make certain subsequent matrix calculations simpler.

$A = U V^T$

Case Study : Linear Algebra In Machine Learning¶

Introduction¶

Linear algebra is a foundational topic in machine learning. From data representation to optimization techniques, the concepts of vectors, matrices, and linear equations play a crucial role. In this case study, we will explore how these concepts are applied in a simple linear regression problem.

Problem Statement¶

You are a data scientist at a real estate company. The company wants to predict the price of houses based on their size (in square feet). You have been provided with a dataset containing the size and price of various houses sold in the past. Your task is to build a linear regression model using the concepts of linear algebra.

Dataset¶

For simplicity, let's consider a small dataset:

Size (sq.ft) Price (in $)
650 77250
785 92850
1200 135000
720 86000
975 110500
In [65]:
# Import necessary libraries
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define the dataset
sizes = np.array([650, 785, 1200, 720, 975])
prices = np.array([77250, 92850, 135000, 86000, 110500])

# Visualize the data
plt.scatter(sizes, prices, color='blue')
plt.xlabel('Size (sq.ft)')
plt.ylabel('Price ($)')
plt.title('House Prices based on Size')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The scatter plot visualizes the relationship between house sizes and their respective prices. It seems there's a linear relationship between the two.

Vectors and Matrices in Linear Regression¶

Linear regression can be represented as:

$y = X \beta + \epsilon$

Where:

  • ( y ) is the vector of target values (prices).
  • ( X ) is the matrix of input features (sizes).
  • $\beta$ is the vector of coefficients.
  • $\epsilon$ is the error term.

To find the best-fitting line, we aim to minimize the error term. Using linear algebra, the coefficients $\beta$ can be found as:

$\beta = (X^T X)^{-1} X^T y$

In [66]:
# Prepare the input matrix X and target vector y
X = np.vstack([np.ones(sizes.shape[0]), sizes]).T
y = prices

# Calculate the coefficients using the normal equation
beta = np.linalg.inv(X.T @ X) @ X.T @ y

print(f"Intercept: {beta[0]:.2f}")
print(f"Slope (Price per sq.ft): {beta[1]:.2f}")

Intercept: 11206.25
Slope (Price per sq.ft): 102.90

The intercept represents the base price of a house regardless of its size, while the slope indicates the price increase per additional square foot.

Predicting House Prices¶

With the coefficients in hand, we can now predict the price of any house given its size.

$\hat{y} = X \beta$

In [67]:
# Predict prices using the linear model
predicted_prices = X @ beta

# Visualize the original data and the best-fitting line
plt.scatter(sizes, prices, color='blue', label='Actual Prices')
plt.plot(sizes, predicted_prices, color='red', label='Predicted Prices')
plt.xlabel('Size (sq.ft)')
plt.ylabel('Price ($)')
plt.title('House Prices Prediction based on Size')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The red line represents the predictions of our linear regression model. As observed, it fits the actual data points quite well, indicating a good model.

Conclusion¶

In this case study, we applied the concepts of vectors, matrices, and linear equations to build a linear regression model. Linear algebra provides the tools and techniques to efficiently compute solutions in machine learning, making it an essential topic for any data scientist or machine learning practitioner.
